items.title: Xanthagrion erythroneurum
items.content_text: On a winter-wet, summer-dry grassland area, road on one side, rail on the other side, no permanent water in the vicinity. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Gastrodia procera
items.content_text: New orchid species record for Riddells Creek. Tallest stem 80cm, perianth tube 20mm, 26 flowers on infloresence, stem is erect at the top when flowers are in bud.

items.title: Tasmannia xerophila subsp. xerophila
items.content_text: One flower visible with 2 petals. Growing in rocks in open herb-field. Altitude ~1470m.

items.title: Hovea montana
items.content_text: Nearly all plants had finished flowering.

items.title: Celmisia pugioniformis
items.content_text: Slender leaves. Seemed to be finishing flowering (flowers scruffy looking) whereas the broad-leaved C. tomentella growing with it hadn't started flowering yet.

items.title: Micrantheum hexandrum
items.content_text: Tiny flowers. 3 petals.

items.title: Grevillea alpivaga
items.content_text: To 1m tall and spreading. Midrib on underside of leaf is visible which suggests it is G. alpivaga, not G. australis. Flowering with Kunzea parvifolia.

items.title: Chrysolarentia correlata
items.content_text: Distinctly yellow in flight and on landing. Gives a few wing flaps on landing before resting. This species might merge with C. insulsata (see CD that comes with Moths of Victoria 3). New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Chrysolarentia nephodes
items.content_text: Gives a few wing flaps after landing then rests with wings held in triangular form. Disturbed one seemingly every few footsteps, but never allowed to get close.

items.title: Rubus fruticosus spp. agg., Trapezites phigalioides
Vanessa kershawi
items.content_text: Looks typical but 3rd pic shows an extra white spot on the upperside of the wing.

items.title: Trapezites eliena
items.content_text: Altitude 1460m. This species recorded in Braby as occurring up to 1200m. Seen fleetingly but orange colour was a stand-out. It is on Westringia senifolia (Alpine Westringia).

items.title: Graphium macleayanus moggana, Westringia senifolia
items.content_text: Host plant for Swallowtail at this location would probably be that described in observation 7933 (Tasmannia xerophila subsp. xerophila).

items.title: Austroargiolestes calcaris
items.content_text: In an alpine stream at the beginning of the Dickson's Falls walk. The bronze might be the sunlight catching it at the right angle.

items.title: Chalcites lucidus
items.content_text: Flew into window. Placed in bush to recover by Barry Best.

items.title: Aenetus ligniveren
items.content_text: Found dead on the garden path this morning. Apparently males are rarely seen. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Taxeotis intextata
items.content_text: Looks like T. mimela but I'm told more likely to be T. intextata which was seen flying on this night. At a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Praxis edwardsii
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek - at a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Leptotarsus (Macromastix) spp.
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek - at a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Unplaced severata
items.content_text: At a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night. ID by MH.

items.title: Phelotis cognata
items.content_text: Near a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Chlorocoma sp. (3)
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek - near a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night. Identified using the Emerald moth key in the newly published 'Moths of Victoria 4'.

items.title: Epidesmia hypenaria
items.content_text: Wings held so moth looks triangular. Very long nose.

items.title: Dermaptera spp.
items.content_text: Spotted by Josh during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Austrogomphus guerini
items.content_text: Spotted resting on Ozothamnus obcordatus by Steve Williams during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Hemianax papuensis
items.content_text: Spotted resting in a Cherry Ballart by the kids during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Harmonia conformis
items.content_text: New species recorded for Riddells Creek. Spotted by Jordan on a Black Wattle during a joint RCLandcare/Entomological Society night.

items.title: Austroargiolestes icteromelas
items.content_text: Very friendly. Initially spotted on concrete by my daughter Ellena.

items.title: Amphibromus nervosus
items.content_text: Growing in a dried out billabong.

items.title: Diptera spp.
items.content_text: Feeding on Lythrum hyssopifolium.

items.title: Coleoptera spp.
items.content_text: On Lythrum hyssopifolia.

items.title: Bibionidae spp., Diptera spp.
items.content_text: Not sure of ID.

items.title: Rytidosperma pallidum
items.content_text: Seems to be flowering earlier than usual?

items.title: Triglochin striata
items.content_text: Growing among Gratiola peruviana on the edge of a pond that is slowly drying up.

items.title: Acacia verniciflua s.l.
items.content_text: Seedpod virtually glabrous (now A. verniciflua s.s.).

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Very hairy seedpod is an important ID feature (now A. rostriformis).

items.title: Papilio anactus
items.content_text: Taken with iPhone.

items.title: Lissopimpla excelsa
items.content_text: Lots around this day.

items.title: Carex inversa
items.content_text: Spotted in the 'lawn'.

items.title: Gratiola peruviana
items.content_text: In an area usually waterlogged - edge of a pool.

items.title: Trapezites phigalioides
items.content_text: Two individuals pictured.

items.title: Eulamprus tympanum tympanum
items.content_text: On Conglomerate rock.

items.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans
items.content_text: Note small moths on 2nd pic (Glyphiptera or Oecophorid moths perhaps).

items.title: Pollanisus viridipulverulenta
items.content_text: About double the size of the similar-looking Turneriprocris dolens, which was flying on the same day - see previous observation, 7802.

items.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans, Turneriprocris dolens
items.content_text: Moth is about half the size of the similar-looking Satin-green Forester, which was also about in large numbers this day (see following observation, 7803). T. dolens seen primarily on the Leucochrysum.

items.title: Aquila audax
items.content_text: Saw it swoop down then up to gradually higher perches. Couldn't see ground but it was disturbed by two kangaroos 30s after swooping down. Perched for 5 minutes.

items.title: Amphibromus nervosus
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. Growing in a drying out Billabong.

items.title: Hesperilla donnysa donnysa
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. 1st pic shows it on stem of its host plant, Gahnia radula, which surrounds an unspoilt Billabong. I saw lots possibly emerging from the base of plants.

items.title: Epilobium billardierianum subsp. intermedium
items.content_text: Keys out quite well to intermedium although the few plants I saw wouldn't be described as freely branching. Two individuals pictured here.

items.title: Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) calophyllae
items.content_text: In Dillwynia cinerascens s.s.. Lines on mesoscutum suggest calophyllae.

items.title: Dillwynia cinerascens s.s., Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) clelandi
items.content_text: Lack of shining on mesoscutum is a good ID feature for clelandi but can never be 100% sure of ID for this group.

items.title: Amphibromus nervosus
items.content_text: Not sure of ID.

items.title: Montia australasica
items.content_text: Fooled me for a while because the first plant had 6 petals (see 3rd pic).

items.title: Isolepis marginata
items.content_text: This has appeared in these recent wet years along with I. hystrix along a semi-disturbed track beside rail line. Not sure of ID (could be cernua var. platycarpa).

items.title: Isolepis cernua var. platycarpa
items.content_text: This tiny plant has been recorded here previously. Glumes look a little acute so can't discount I. marginata.

items.title: Amyema pendula subsp. pendula (s.s.)
items.content_text: Growing on Allocasuarina verticillata.

items.title: 116 ids
items.content_text: Species list for collection.

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. angustissimus
items.content_text: New plant for Riddells Creek. 1st pic shows upper leaves, 2nd shows distinctive mid-stem leaves.

items.title: Potamogeton cheesemanii
items.content_text: New record for Riddells Creek. What looks like a natural billabong with original flora pretty much intact.

items.title: Gladiolus cardinalis
items.content_text: A few plants in a (weedy) bush setting. One record on FIS and none at the Herbarium. Got to be a contender for 'prettiest weed'!

items.title: Isolepis levynsiana
items.content_text: In a winter-inundated, summer-dry depression made a little deeper by tyre tracks.

items.title: Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: On A. mearnsii. Many plants in the area dead or defoliated. Many still healthy too. In this this area A. leprosa var. uninervia is also being seriously damaged or killed (apparently by a very similar but different species).

items.title: Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: This small A. mearnsii plant was covered in beetles.

items.title: Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: On Acacia mearnsii - plant only defoliated a small amount but mearnsii all but disappeared from this location a couple of years ago. A few new plants returned last year and this year. On the volcanic plains.

items.title: Petrorhagia dubia
items.content_text: 3rd pic shows ID features. 1) Densely glandular-tomentose mid-stem between leaf nodes. 2) Leaf sheath twice as long as stem width. 3) Seed tuberculate, 1-1.3mm (0.5mm marks on ruler in pic).

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. uninervia, Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: What looks like Fireblight Beetle attacking Acacia leprosa. All plants at this spot seem to be dead or seriously damaged. Two individuals photographed.

items.title: Cassinia longifolia
items.content_text: Lovely pink-bud form of Cassinia longifolia. One seen in Sandy Ck Reserve last week too. I think they end up white-flowered.

items.title: Isolepis hystrix
items.content_text: Tiny plants in a clay pan - winter inundation, summer dry.

items.title: Thelymitra pauciflora s.l.
items.content_text: Two populations found, adjacent but not overlapping (could be the same species) - see photos in this and the previous observation (differences in post-anther lobes and distribution of hairs in lateral lobes).

items.title: Thelymitra pauciflora s.l.
items.content_text: Slender (not robust). Plants with probably a median of 4 flowers.

items.title: Calomela parilis
items.content_text: On Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata. ID by Chris Read, via Ken Walker.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
items.content_text: T-Hill Reserve.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. graveolens (2)
items.content_text: Patch of about 10 plants. Only the second group of plants seen in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. angustissimus
items.content_text: Distinctive leaves on this subspecies. I was once told they are sometimes seen growing with subsp. omnigracilis and they are obviously different when seen together. It is true. See also obs 7616.

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. omnigracilis
items.content_text: omnigracilis means 'all bits' slender, referring to the thin lobes on all leaves.

items.title: Caladenia moschata
items.content_text: Strong musky smell. 2-3 times taller than C. praecox and much later flowering.

items.title: Tiliqua nigrolutea
items.content_text: Very grey individual.

items.title: Thelymitra arenaria
items.content_text: 1st pic shows hairs extend almost the entire length of lateral lobes and notched post-anther lobe. 2nd pic shows 9 flowers on one stem. 3rd shows leaf can extend almost as high as the flowers.

items.title: Thelymitra juncifolia
items.content_text: Tiny flowers (slightly smaller than $2 coin) seems to rule out T. ixioides. Both species have been recorded in the general area.

items.title: Arthropodium strictum s.s.
items.content_text: Not recorded previously at this site. Different individuals photographed.

items.title: Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) cognatum
items.content_text: Looks like it is in Geranium retrorsum. ID by KW.

items.title: Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) spp.
items.content_text: In Arthropodium strictum s.s. (Chocolate Lily). ID by KW.

items.title: Homalictus punctatus
items.content_text: Looks like it is in Geranium solanderi var. solanderi s.s.. ID by KW.

items.title: Pseudalmenus chlorinda zephyrus
items.content_text: Flying around and landing on a few young bipinnate wattles (Acacia mearnsii and dealbata). Only one adult seen. Some of the A. mearnsii plants here seem to be suffering from Fireblight beetle attack.

items.title: Geranium solanderi var. solanderi s.s.
items.content_text: Showing purple dehiscence lines on anthers and spreading hairs on stem.

items.title: Geranium sp. 3
items.content_text: Shows dark dehiscence lines on anthers. Doesn't seem to have been recorded here previously.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Two roadside plants opposite a patch of A. verniciflua (Common Variant). Very hairy peduncle and all leaves rostriform. Plants 3-4m tall, upright. Suspect these plants were erroneously planted here.

items.title: Acacia acinacea s.s.
items.content_text: Small copse of plants, with every leaf perfectly rostriform in shape (pointed leaf tip bent to one side). Plants all 60-80cm tall.

items.title: Hakea salicifolia subsp. salicifolia
items.content_text: Very pretty weed!

items.title: Acacia aculeatissima
items.content_text: Sprawling (almost-)groundcover, prickly leaves irregularly arranged on stem and mostly pointing in the one direction.

items.title: Dillwynia ramosissima
items.content_text: Leaves in clusters.

items.title: Acacia verniciflua s.l.
items.content_text: Shows glabrous to sparsely hairy peduncle, 2 veins on leaf (one less conspicuous), punctate leaf surface, central mucro on leaf tip and longitudinal 'bands' on penultimate branchlet.

items.title: Anthochaera carunculata
items.content_text: Nice wattles. In garden-planted Gippsland Waratah (Telopea oreades).

items.title: Phascolarctos cinereus
items.content_text: Climbing up Eucalyptus viminalis. He started calling as we stood beneath him.

items.title: Kennedia prostrata
items.content_text: Great displays this year.

items.title: Carex appressa
items.content_text: 3-angled stem, broad leaves.

items.title: Sonchus asper s.s., Sonchus asper subsp. glaucescens
Viola hederacea sensu Thiele & Prober
items.content_text: Purple in bud. All flowers fully open. Strong purple colour in flower centre. Relatively short peduncles. See 7479 for comparison with new species.

items.title: Viola spp.
items.content_text: White in bud. Only one flower 'open' (remainder 'closed' & nodding) on this warm day (flowers open more on hotter days). Light purple venation in flower centre. Relatively long peduncles. See 7480 for comparison with Viola hederacea.

items.title: Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) calophyllae, Pultenaea daphnoides
items.content_text: Native bee in remnant pea - no Apis mellifera in this plant, native bees only.

items.title: Candalides hyacinthina hyacinthina
items.content_text: On Pultenaea mollis.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. graveolens
items.content_text:
Recently renamed as Acacia leprosa var. graveolens. This one is about 8m tall.
syn. Acacia verniciflua (southern variant)

items.content_text: Features: drooping stem when in bud (like Yam Daisy); stem unbranched; leaves in basal rosette; leaf strongly lobed; base of leaf very hairy and getting less hairy toward leaf tip (stems also hairier at base).
